Solution: The dissociation energy \(D_e\) is calculated from the given \(D_0\), \(\omega_e = \nu_e / c = 1405.65 \, \text{cm}^{-1}\), and \(\omega_e x_e = \nu_e x_e / c = 23.20 \, \text{cm}^{-1}\). The relationship is \(D_e = D_0 + \text{ZPE}\), where the zero-point energy (ZPE) is given by \(\text{ZPE} = \frac{1}{2} \omega_e - \frac{1}{4} \omega_e x_e\).

